node.title: U.S. health officials urge vaccinations as Omicron spreads.
node.description: Getting a vaccination is the best line of defense against Covid-19, the nation’s top two health leaders said on Sunday.

node.title: Scott Morrison says National Cabinet to meet to discuss Omicron COVID variant
node.description: The Prime Minister says he is planning on calling a meeting of state and territory leaders today or tomorrow to discuss how to respond to the Omicron variant, but it is "too early" to make decisions about reinstating quarantine before Christmas.

node.title: Police officer hit by fleeing car in Auckland
node.description: A police officer is in Auckland Hospital with serious injuries after being hit by a fleeing driver in Tāmaki Makaurau..

node.title: Stephen Sondheim, as Great a Composer as He Was a Lyricist
node.description: Our chief classical music critic remembers playing and teaching the unforgettable scores of “Sweeney Todd,” “Sunday in the Park With George” and other shows.

node.title: ‘Encanto’ Reaches No. 1, but Moviegoers Are Tough to Lure Back
node.description: No simultaneous streaming: “Encanto” or “House of Gucci” could only be seen in theaters this weekend. Even still, some viewers stayed home.

node.title: Phil Saviano, Survivor of Clergy Sex Abuse, Dies at 69
node.description: He played a pivotal role in helping The Boston Globe uncover the widespread scandal in the Catholic Church and was portrayed in the movie “Spotlight.”

node.title: Man Arrested for Allegedly Beating to Death Infant Left in His Care
node.description: An autopsy found that the large skull fracture "due to blunt force trauma on the right side of [the child's] head" was the most likely cause of death, said authorities.

node.title: Public servants have been told to return to the office, but what risk do they face as COVID-19 remains in the community?
node.description: Federal public servants have been told to return to the office in the wake of eased COVID-19 restrictions, sparking debate over whether it is the safest approach as the virus continues to circulate in the community.

node.title: By dethroning a would-be king, George Kambosos Jr sits atop Australian boxing
node.description: George Kambosos Jr’s stunning win over Teófimo López could lay claim to being the best ever by an Australian overseas, making Kambosos Australian boxing’s current number one, writes Simon Smale.

node.title: Louis Vuitton's star designer Virgil Abloh dies of cancer
node.description: Designer Virgil Abloh, a leading fashion executive hailed as the Karl Lagerfeld of his generation, has died of cancer.

node.title: New COVID-19 variant, Omicron, set alarm bells ringing over the weekend. Here's what you need to know
node.description: The Omicron variant has been declared a COVID-19 "variant of concern" by the World Health Organization as cases start appearing in countries well away from southern Africa. Here's everything that happened over the weekend regarding this new variant.

node.title: Virgil Abloh, famed fashion designer, dies of cancer at 41
node.description: Abloh, 41, battled cardiac angiosarcoma, a rare, aggressive form of cancer.

node.title: Israel and Morocco impose blanket bans on all foreign travelers.
node.description: The travel bans appeared more drastic but less discriminatory than those implemented by many Western nations.

node.title: Texas Teen Confesses to Fatally Shooting Mother in Head: Police
node.description: Authorities said that the 15-year-old male "provided a full confession to the Homicide detective" and will be charged with capital murder.

node.title: Woman Punches Flight Attendants, Pulls Their Hair Until Fellow Passenger Zip-Ties Her Feet
node.description: She allegedly told police "shoot me motherf******" and "I didn't do anything wrong" after they arrested her.

node.title: Australia's first cases of Omicron COVID-19 strain detected in Sydney travellers
node.description: NSW Health confirms two returned travellers have tested positive for the new Omicron COVID-19 variant in Sydney, making them the first known cases in the country.

node.title: What happens when your builder goes bust? For some, their life savings disappear
node.description: Kate and Rod Iskander can only look on in despair at what should be their new home — a building site littered with bricks and hardening bags of cement. Their builder went bust two months ago and they've already sunk their life savings.

node.title: Covid-19: Last-minute rush for pre-Christmas vaccinations
node.description: Vaccinations in Auckland this weekend have showed no sign of slowing down with over 200 doses given in three hours on Sunday.

node.title: Virgil Abloh, Bold Designer of Men’s Wear, Dies at 41
node.description: His expansive approach to design inspired comparisons to artists including Andy Warhol and Jeff Koons. For him, clothes were totems of identity.

node.title: Jennifer Nettles Had Sung ‘She Used to Be Mine.’ But Not While Crying.
node.description: The country singer and musical-theater fan was grateful to play the intense title role in “Waitress” not long after her Broadway-themed album came out.

node.title: The COVID-19 pandemic positives for Australians living with disabilities
node.description: From the blind photographer observing details, to living solo for the first time, or discovering the power of roller skating — the pandemic for these Australians living with disabilities has been a chance to find joy, independence and new passions.

node.title: The COVID-19 tests expected to form a 'line of defence' when WA opens its doors to the world
node.description: When Western Australia finally opens its doors to the rest of the world – potentially letting in the Omicron variant of COVID-19 – rapid antigen self-tests could form an important line of defence to prevent  outbreaks in high-risk settings.

node.title: Susan Neill-Fraser will find out tomorrow if she can walk free from prison — here's what her appeal is about
node.description: Neill-Fraser has been fighting to clear her name ever since she was charged with murdering her partner, Bob Chappell, in 2009. A decision in her latest appeal will be handed down almost nine months after her lawyers argued there has been a miscarriage of justice.

node.title: There's backlash to China's LGBTQI+ movement — but it's not lead by religious groups
node.description: Queer communities in China are increasingly seen as a political threat to state stability, writes Jinghua Qian.

node.title: How Nas Campanella's TV debut helped her think about motherhood
node.description: Years ago Nas Campanella played a pregnant woman on prime time TV. The experience made her feel conflicted — but it also helped her think about motherhood.

node.title: Slip south of Gisborne destroys wāhi tapu and hopes of railway's reinstatement
node.description: A huge slip along the mothballed rail line between Gisborne and Wairoa has destroyed sacred Māori whenua and dashed hopes of the railway being reinstated.

node.title: Listen to Stephen Sondheim’s 20 Essential Songs
node.description: The lyricist and composer, who died on Friday, wrote dozens of piercing tunes for Broadway. Here is a selection of them, as lean as a Sondheim couplet.

node.title: Housing affordability is a national crisis, but for one group of young people it can be life changing
node.description: The housing affordability crisis is being felt acutely by young people with a disability, partly because the hidden costs of having a disability can make it much more difficult to save a deposit and pay off a mortgage.

node.title: Father manufactures medicine for sick son in China after COVID-19 limits treatment
node.description: A desperate father is manufacturing medicine for his sick son after he was unable to get treatment in his country due to COVID-19.

node.title: Ashlie used to help feed the homeless, now at 64 she's homeless herself
node.description: After falling into an unexpected cycle of disadvantage, Ashlie Stevenson is one of hundreds of thousands of Australians languishing on waiting lists for public housing.
